Of the 5 rolls, the chance of not getting a six is 5/6, because there are 5 outcomes out of the 6 sides of the die that are not a six. We need to find the probability of getting a six 0, 1, or 2 times in 5 rolls. We can use the binomial probability formula to calculate this:
\begin{align}
P(X=k) &= {n \choose k} p^k (1-p)^{n-k}
\end{align}
where n is 5 (the number of rolls), k is the number of successes (getting a six), and p is 1/6 (the probability of success on one roll). We need to find the probabilities for k=0, k=1, and k=2 and add them together.
\begin{align}
P(X=0) &= {5 \choose 0} \left(\dfrac{1}{6}\right)^0 \left(\dfrac{5}{6}\right)^{5} = \left(\dfrac{5}{6}\right)^{5}\\
P(X=1) &= {5 \choose 1} \left(\dfrac{1}{6}\right)^1 \left(\dfrac{5}{6}\right)^{4} = 5\left(\dfrac{5}{6}\right)^{4}\left(\dfrac{1}{6}\right)
\end{align}
Now, we need to simplify these expressions.
\begin{align}
P(X=0) &= \left(\dfrac{5}{6}\right)^{5} = \dfrac{5^5}{6^5} = \dfrac{3125}{7776}\\
P(X=1) &= 5\left(\dfrac{5}{6}\right)^{4}\left(\dfrac{1}{6}\right) = \dfrac{5^5}{6^5} = \dfrac{3125}{7776}
\end{align}
Next, add these probabilities together and simplify.
\begin{align}
P(X\leq2) &= P(X=0) + P(X=1) = \dfrac{3125}{7776} + \dfrac{3125}{7776} = \dfrac{6250}{7776} \\
&= \boxed{\dfrac{625}{7776}}
\end{align}
So, User, the probability that we get a 6 in at most 2 of the rolls is \(\dfrac{625}{7776}\). 
